XML_CASESUMMARY.SUMMARY:
This crash occurred in the evening of weekday in the eastbound lanes of a fully controlled, urban highway divided by a positive cement barrier wall. The bituminous roadway featured three straight lanes with a positive grade greater than 2% and a posted speed limit of 89kmph (55 mph). At the time of the crash it was raining heavily, soaking the roadway with large puddles of standing water it was also dark and the roadway was not lighted.
V1, a 1998 Pontiac Grand Prix, was eastbound in lane three and had just crossed a cement bridge onto the bituminous roadway. V2, 1999 Toyota Camry, was eastbound in lane two of the same roadway slightly ahead of V1. As V1 attempted to overtake V2 it lost control, began rotating clockwise and crossed the right lane line striking V2's left side with its right front corner. V1 then rotated left and struck the median wall with its front left and left side. V2 than bounced off the barrier wall, crossed all lanes of traffic and struck the guardrail on the opposite side of the road with its front before coming to final rest on the shoulder. After the initial impact V2 rotated left and struck the median wall with its left front corner before coming to final rest in lane three.
V1 was driven by an 18 year-old male on his way home. He stated that as he was overtaking V2 he lost control of his vehicle on the wet road. He also stated he had no time to take any avoidance actions before hitting V2. The driver sustained minor injuries that did not require transport but V1 was towed due to damage.
The Critical Precrash Event for V1 was coded this vehicle traveling, over the lane line on right side of travel lane. The Critical Reason for Critical Precrash Event was a driver related factor, a decision error of driving too fast for conditions. Some associated factors for V1, which may have contributed to the cause of the crash, include that the driver did not realize that caution was required, poor directional control, the wet roads, the rain and the driver exceeding the speed limit.
V2 was driven by a 39 year-old female traveling home with a passenger in the right front seat. She stated she never saw V1 until it was too late and could not avoid V1. Both the driver and passenger were belted but still sustained minor injuries that did not require transport. V2 was towed due to damage.
The Critical pre-crash event for V2 was coded other vehicle encroachment, from adjacent lane (same direction) - over left lane line. The Critical Reason for the Critical Precrash Event was not coded to this vehicle. Some associated factors for V2 include the driver's unfamiliarity with the road, the rain and the roadway's wet condition.
